      • markEphemeral

        public void markEphemeral()
        Description copied from interface: DfaMemoryState
        Ephemeral means a state that was created when considering a method contract and checking if one of its arguments is null. With explicit null check, that would result in any non-annotated variable being treated as nullable and producing possible NPE warnings later. With contracts, we don't want this. So the state where this variable is null is marked ephemeral and no NPE warnings are issued for such states.
        Specified by:
        markEphemeral in interface DfaMemoryState

      • setDfType

        public void setDfType(DfaValue value,
                      DfType dfType)
        Description copied from interface: DfaMemoryState
        Forcibly sets the supplied dfType to given value if given value state can be memoized. This is necessary to override some knowledge about the variable state. In most of the cases DfaMemoryState.meetDfType(DfaValue, DfType) should be used as it narrows existing type.
        Specified by:
        setDfType in interface DfaMemoryState
        Parameters:
        value - value to update.
        dfType - type to assign to value. Note that type might be adjusted, e.g. to be compatible with value declared PsiType.

      • meetDfType

        public boolean meetDfType(DfaValue value,
                          DfType dfType)
        Description copied from interface: DfaMemoryState
        Updates value dfType if it's compatible with current value state. Depending on value passed and memory state implementation the new fact may or may not be memoized.
        Specified by:
        meetDfType in interface DfaMemoryState
        Parameters:
        value - value to update
        dfType - wanted type
        Returns:
        true if update was successful. If false was returned the memory state may be in inconsistent state.
